To identify a compound adjective in a sentence and output it using Java code, you can use natural language processing (NLP) libraries like the POS (Part of Speech) tagger in the Stanford CoreNLP library. First, you need to install the library and add it to your project's dependencies.

**Steps to install the Stanford CoreNLP library:**

1. Download the library from this [link](https://nlp.stanford.edu/software/stanford-corenlp-full-2021-10-30.tar.gz).
2. Extract the downloaded file.
3. In your IDE, add the Stanford CoreNLP library to your project's dependencies by adding the following lines to your `build.gradle` file:
```groovy
dependencies {
    implementation 'edu.stanford.nlp:stanford-corenlp:3.10.0'
}
```
After setting up the library, you can write a Java code snippet to parse the sentence and output the compound adjective:
```java
import edu.stanford.nlp.ling.CoreAnnotations;
import edu.stanford.nlp.ling.TaggedWord;
import edu.stanford.nlp.pipeline.Annotation;
import edu.stanford.nlp.pipeline.StanfordCoreNLP;
import edu.stanford.nlp.util.CoreMap;

import java.util.List;

public class CompoundAdjectiveIdentification {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String sentence = "The owner drove an old, rusty car.";

        StanfordCoreNLP pipeline = new StanfordCoreNLP("tokenize", "parse");
        Annotation annotation = pipeline.process(sentence);
        List<CoreMap> sentences = annotation.get(CoreAnnotations.SentencesAnnotation.class);

        if (sentences.size() > 0) {
            CoreMap sentenceAnnotation = sentences.get(0);
            List<CoreMap> tokens = sentenceAnnotation.get(CoreAnnotations.TokensAnnotation.class);
            List<CoreMap> posTags = sentenceAnnotation.get(CoreAnnotations.PartOfSpeechAnnotation.class);

            for (int i = 0; i < tokens.size(); i++) {
                CoreMap tokenAnnotation = tokens.get(i);
                String word = tokenAnnotation.get(CoreAnnotations.WordAnnotation.class);
                String pos = posTags.get(i).get(CoreAnnotations.PartOfSpeechTagAnnotation.class);

                if (pos.equals("JJ")) { // Check if the word is an adjective
                    if (word.equals("old")) {
                        System.out.println("Old: " + word);
                    }
                    if (word.equals("rusty")) {
                        System.out.println("Rusty: " + word);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
In this example, the code identifies adjectives in the sentence and outputs them. You can modify the code to specifically identify compound adjectives by checking if the adjectives appear next to each other and are connected by a comma.

