To create a script that copies a range of cells in Google Spreadsheets and pastes it into another sheet, you can use Google Apps Script. Here's a step-by-step guide to create a script that does what you described:

1. Open your Google Spreadsheet.
2. Click on "Tools" in the top menu, then select "Script editor" (you may need to enable the "Developer" mode in the settings to see this option).
3. In the script editor, delete any existing code (if present) and replace it with the following script:
```javascript
function copyRangeToAnotherSheet() {
  var sourceSheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheetByName("Sheet3");
  var targetSheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheetByName("Sheet4");
  var sourceRange = sourceSheet.getRange("A1:F1");
  var targetRange = targetSheet.getRange(2, 1, sourceRange.getNumCells(), sourceRange.getNumCells());
  sourceRange.copyTo(targetRange);
}
```
4. Save the script by clicking on the floppy disk icon or pressing `Ctrl + S` (or `Cmd + S` on a Mac).
5. Go back to your Google Spreadsheet.
6. Click on the button you want to use to trigger the script.
7. Click on the three dots next to the button, then select "Assign script".
8. Select the `copyRangeToAnotherSheet` function from the list of available functions.
9. Click "Save".
10. Now, when you click on the button, the script will run and copy the range A1:F1 from Sheet3 to the 2nd row of Sheet4.

Note: Make sure that the sheet names in the script correspond to the actual names of the sheets in your Spreadsheet.

