The ps command in xv6 allows a user to view information about the current processes running on the system. To implement this command, you need to add a new system call to xv6, which is `getprocs()`. This system call will provide the user-space program (ps) with information about the processes running in the system.

First, you need to add the `getprocs()` system call to the `sysproc.c` file in the xv6 kernel. The function definition for `sys_getprocs()` is as follows:
```c
int sys_getprocs(void)
{
    int size;
    struct uproc *buf;
    struct proc *p = getptable_proc();
    char *pbuf;

    if (argint(0, &size) < 0)
        return -1;
    if (argptr(1, &pbuf, size * sizeof(struct uproc)) < 0)
        return -1;

    buf = (struct uproc *)pbuf;

    while (p != 0) {
        // copy information from the proc struct to the uproc struct
        // ...
        p = p->next;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
The `sys_getprocs()` function takes two arguments: an integer `size` and a pointer to a buffer `buf`. The `size` argument specifies the maximum number of processes that the user wants to retrieve. The `buf` pointer points to a memory area where the kernel will store the information about the processes.

Inside the function, the kernel iterates through the process table (`getptable_proc()` returns a pointer to the first element of the process table) and copies the information about each process to the corresponding element of the `buf` buffer.

Next, you need to modify the `ps.c` user-space program to call the `getprocs()` system call and output the process information. The modified `ps.c` code is as follows:
```c
#include "types.h"
#include "stat.h"
#include "user.h"

// From proc.h Proc structure
// Per-process state
enum procstate { UNUSED, EMBRYO, SLEEPING, RUNNABLE, RUNNING, ZOMBIE };
struct uproc {
    int pid;
    int ppid;
    int state;
    uint sz;
    char name[16];
};

#define MAX_PROC 10

int
main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    struct uproc ptable[MAX_PROC];
    struct uproc *p;
    int err;

    err = getprocs(10, ptable);
    if (err != 0)
        printf(1, "Error getting ptable");

    // output the process details
    for (p = ptable; p < ptable + MAX_PROC && p->pid != 0; p++)
        printf(2, "pid: %d, ppid: %d, state: %s, size: %d, name: %s\n", p->pid, p->ppid, procstate[p->state], p->sz, p->name);

    exit();
}
```
Lastly, you need to define the `getprocs()` system call in `uproc.h` and implement it in `proc.c`. The `getprocs()` function takes two arguments, an integer `max` that specifies the maximum number of processes to retrieve, and a pointer to a buffer `table` where the kernel will store the process information. The function returns the actual number of processes in existence, or -1 if there was an error.
```c
// uproc.h
int getprocs(int max, struct uproc table[]);
```

```c
// proc.c

int
getprocs(int max, struct uproc table[])
{
    struct proc *p = getptable_proc();
    int count = 0;

    while (p != 0 && count < max) {
        table[count].pid = p->pid;
        table[count].ppid = p->parent->pid;
        table[count].state = p->state;
        table[count].sz = p->sz;
        // copy the name of the process (up to 15 characters)
        strncpy(table[count].name, p->name, 15);
        table[count].name[14] = '\0';
        p = p->next;
        count++;
    }

