To display the preview of the PDF files and images in your React app, you can follow these steps:

1. **Setup a new endpoint in your Java backend to serve the files:** You will create a new route in your backend that serves the file from S3 as a stream (streaming), allowing you to display the preview without converting the S3 files to public.

Here's a Java snippet using AWS SDK to serve a file from a private S3 bucket:

```java
import com.amazonaws.services.s3.AmazonS3;
import com.amazonaws.services.s3.model.GetObjectRequest;
import com.amazonaws.services.s3.model.S3Object;
import org.springframework.core.io.InputStreamResource;
import org.springframework.http.MediaType;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PathVariable;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
public class FileController {
    private final AmazonS3 amazonS3;
    private final String bucketName = "your-private-s3-bucket";

    public FileController(AmazonS3 amazonS3) {
        this.amazonS3 = amazonS3;
    }

    @GetMapping("/s3-files/{filename}.{extension}")
    public ResponseEntity<InputStreamResource> getFile(@PathVariable String filename, @PathVariable String extension) {
        // Prepare getFileRequest
        GetObjectRequest getObjectRequest = new GetObjectRequest(bucketName, filename + "." + extension);
        S3Object s3Object = amazonS3.getObject(getObjectRequest);

        // Serve the file as InputStreamResource
        InputStreamResource inputStreamResource = new InputStreamResource(s3Object.getObjectContent());

        // Set a suitable MediaType
        MediaType mediaType;
        if (extension.equalsIgnoreCase("pdf")) {
            mediaType = MediaType.APPLICATION_PDF;
        } else if (extension.equalsIgnoreCase("jpg") || extension.equalsIgnoreCase("jpeg")) {
            mediaType = MediaType.IMAGE_JPEG;
        } else if (extension.equalsIgnoreCase("png")) {
            mediaType = MediaType.IMAGE_PNG;
        } else {
            mediaType = MediaType.APPLICATION_OCTET_STREAM;
        }

        return ResponseEntity.ok()
                .contentType(mediaType)
                .body(inputStreamResource);
    }
}
```

2. **Updating the frontend React App**: In your React app, you can utilize the `embed` tag for PDF files and the `img` tag for images to display the files, set the `src` attribute to point to the Java backend route you just set up.

Here's a minimal sample of a React component that displays a PDF and an image using the endpoint we created in step 1:

```javascript
import React from "react";

const FilePreview = () => {
  const pdfUrl = "/s3-files/sample-file.pdf";
  const imageUrl = "/s3-files/sample-image.png";

  return (
    <div>
      <div>
        <embed
          src={pdfUrl}
          type="application/pdf"
          width="100%"
          height="600px"
        />
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src={imageUrl} alt="Sample" />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default FilePreview;
```

This way, you can display PDF files and images in your React app without making them public in S3.

